{
  "executive_summary": "Event sourcing is a strong architectural fit for this loan application audit trail requirement. The compliance demands — full field-change history, point-in-time state reconstruction, and immutable audit logs — are precisely the problems event sourcing was designed to solve. However, event sourcing introduces significant operational complexity (event schema evolution, projection rebuilds, eventual consistency) that must be weighed against simpler alternatives like a Change Data Capture (CDC) + immutable audit log table pattern. I recommend event sourcing for the loan application bounded context specifically, with a CQRS read model for operational queries, but caution against adopting it platform-wide.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Loan Command Service",
        "responsibility": "Accepts commands (SubmitApplication, UpdateIncome, ChangeStatus, etc.), validates business rules against current state, and emits domain events. Rejects invalid state transitions.",
        "boundaries": "Owns write-side logic. No direct database reads for UI queries. Reconstructs aggregate state from event stream before processing each command."
      },
      {
        "name": "Loan Event Store",
        "responsibility": "Append-only, immutable persistence of all domain events. Each event is keyed by aggregate ID (loan application ID) + sequence number. Supports reading all events for an aggregate and subscribing to new events.",
        "boundaries": "No updates or deletes permitted. Schema: (aggregate_id, sequence_number, event_type, event_data, metadata, timestamp). The metadata envelope captures who, when, correlation ID, and causation ID."
      },
      {
        "name": "Loan Query Service (CQRS Read Side)",
        "responsibility": "Maintains denormalized read models (projections) built by replaying and subscribing to events. Serves operational queries: current application status, application lists, search, dashboards.",
        "boundaries": "Eventually consistent with the event store. Can be rebuilt from scratch by replaying all events. Multiple projections can coexist for different query needs."
      },
      {
        "name": "Audit Projection",
        "responsibility": "A specialized read model optimized for compliance queries: 'show me all changes to application X', 'reconstruct state at timestamp T', 'who changed field Y'. Indexed by application ID, timestamp, field name, and actor.",
        "boundaries": "Read-only. Derived entirely from the event store. Can be rebuilt independently without affecting other projections."
      },
      {
        "name": "Snapshot Store",
        "responsibility": "Periodically stores materialized aggregate state to avoid replaying entire event history for long-lived loan applications. Snapshots are an optimization, not a source of truth.",
        "boundaries": "Optional. Snapshots can be discarded and rebuilt. The event store remains the authoritative source."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "API Gateway / UI",
        "to": "Loan Command Service",
        "contract": "Commands: SubmitLoanApplication, UpdateApplicantInfo, ChangeLoanStatus, AddDocument, etc. Each command includes actor identity (user ID, role), correlation ID, and payload.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — command DTOs, no shared domain objects"
      },
      {
        "from": "Loan Command Service",
        "to": "Loan Event Store",
        "contract": "Append events with optimistic concurrency (expected version number). Events: ApplicationSubmitted, ApplicantInfoUpdated, StatusChanged, DocumentAttached, etc. Each event includes full before/after field values.",
        "coupling_type": "tight — command service depends on event store API directly"
      },
      {
        "from": "Loan Event Store",
        "to": "Loan Query Service",
        "contract": "Event subscription (push) or polling (pull). Query service receives ordered stream of events and updates projections.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — subscription-based, query service can lag behind"
      },
      {
        "from": "Loan Event Store",
        "to": "Audit Projection",
        "contract": "Same event subscription. Audit projection builds compliance-specific views from the same event stream.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — independent projection, no coupling to other read models"
      },
      {
        "from": "API Gateway / UI",
        "to": "Loan Query Service",
        "contract": "Queries: GetApplicationById, SearchApplications, GetApplicationHistory, ReconstructStateAtTime(appId, timestamp). Returns DTOs, not domain objects.",
        "coupling_type": "loose — read-only DTOs"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "1) User issues a command (e.g., UpdateApplicantIncome). 2) Command Service loads aggregate by replaying events from Event Store (or from latest snapshot + subsequent events). 3) Command Service validates business rules against current state. 4) If valid, new event(s) are appended to Event Store with optimistic concurrency check. 5) Event Store notifies subscribers. 6) Query Service and Audit Projection update their read models asynchronously. 7) Read queries hit the denormalized projections, not the event store. For audit reconstruction: replay events up to target timestamp to rebuild exact state.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Event Sourcing",
        "rationale": "Directly satisfies all three compliance requirements: (1) every event captures a field change with actor and timestamp, giving full change history; (2) replaying events to a point in time reconstructs exact state; (3) append-only event store is inherently immutable. This is the textbook use case for event sourcing — regulated domains where audit trail is a first-class requirement, not an afterthought."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "CQRS (Command Query Responsibility Segregation)",
        "rationale": "Event sourcing makes direct queries impractical (you'd have to replay events for every read). CQRS separates the write model (event stream) from read models (projections), allowing optimized query patterns without compromising the event-sourced write side."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Domain Events with Metadata Envelope",
        "rationale": "Each event carries a metadata envelope: { actor_id, actor_role, timestamp, correlation_id, causation_id, source_ip }. This satisfies the 'who changed what and when' requirement at the infrastructure level, not as an application concern."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Optimistic Concurrency Control",
        "rationale": "Prevents lost-update anomalies. When appending events, the expected aggregate version is checked. If another command modified the aggregate concurrently, the append fails and the command is retried. Critical for financial data integrity."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Snapshot Pattern",
        "rationale": "Loan applications may accumulate hundreds of events over their lifecycle (months to years). Periodic snapshots prevent aggregate reconstruction from becoming a performance bottleneck."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Loan Origination",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": [
          {
            "name": "LoanApplication",
            "root_entity": "LoanApplication (identified by applicationId)",
            "invariants": [
              "Status transitions follow a defined state machine (e.g., Draft → Submitted → UnderReview → Approved/Denied → Funded/Withdrawn)",
              "Certain fields are immutable after submission (e.g., loan type)",
              "Required documents must be attached before status can move to UnderReview",
              "Applicant identity cannot change after submission without a formal amendment event"
            ],
            "events": [
              "ApplicationCreated",
              "ApplicantInfoUpdated { changedFields: [{field, oldValue, newValue}] }",
              "ApplicationSubmitted",
              "StatusChanged { from, to, reason }",
              "DocumentAttached { documentId, documentType }",
              "UnderwritingDecisionRecorded { decision, conditions }",
              "ApplicationAmended { amendmentReason, changedFields }",
              "ApplicationWithdrawn { reason }"
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Identity & Access",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": [
          {
            "name": "User",
            "root_entity": "User (provides actor identity for event metadata)",
            "invariants": [],
            "events": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "name": "Compliance & Audit",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": [
          {
            "name": "AuditTrail (read model, not a true aggregate)",
            "root_entity": "Projection built from Loan Origination events",
            "invariants": [
              "Audit records are never modified or deleted",
              "Audit trail must be reconstructable from source events"
            ],
            "events": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Loan Origination",
        "downstream": "Compliance & Audit",
        "relationship": "Published Language — Loan Origination publishes domain events in a well-defined schema. Compliance subscribes and builds audit projections. No back-pressure or upstream dependency."
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Identity & Access",
        "downstream": "Loan Origination",
        "relationship": "Conformist — Loan Origination accepts the user identity model as-is for event metadata (actor_id, role). No translation needed."
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "Use event sourcing instead of audit log table + triggers",
      "gains": "Audit is a natural byproduct, not a bolt-on. Point-in-time reconstruction is exact (replay events). No risk of audit log diverging from actual state. Events become a reusable integration backbone.",
      "sacrifices": "Significantly higher implementation complexity. Team must learn new paradigms (CQRS, projections, event schema evolution). Operational burden increases (projection rebuilds, event store maintenance). Simple queries become harder.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "CDC (Change Data Capture) + immutable audit table: Simpler to implement. Database triggers or CDC tools (Debezium) capture row-level changes into an audit table. Satisfies 'who/what/when' and immutability. However, point-in-time state reconstruction requires replaying the audit log manually — possible but not as clean. Risk: triggers can be bypassed or misconfigured. Good enough for many regulated systems.",
        "Bi-temporal modeling: Two time dimensions (valid time + transaction time) on the loan table itself. Rows are never updated, only new temporal versions inserted. Satisfies all requirements with standard SQL queries. Simpler than event sourcing but makes the relational schema more complex and queries harder to write correctly.",
        "Append-only table with version column: Each 'update' inserts a new row with an incremented version. Current state = max version. Simple, works with standard SQL. Lacks the semantic richness of events (you see state snapshots, not intent-revealing changes)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "CQRS with separate read models",
      "gains": "Read models can be optimized independently for operational queries vs. audit queries. Compliance team gets purpose-built views. Read and write scaling are independent.",
      "sacrifices": "Eventual consistency between write and read side. UI must handle the possibility that a just-submitted change isn't immediately queryable. More infrastructure to maintain (projection workers, read databases).",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Synchronous projection updates in the same transaction: Eliminates eventual consistency but couples write performance to projection complexity. Viable if event volume is low (likely for loan applications)."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Store granular field-level change events rather than state snapshot events",
      "gains": "Audit trail shows exactly which fields changed with old/new values. Enables compliance queries like 'show all income changes across all applications'. Reveals intent.",
      "sacrifices": "Events are more verbose. Schema evolution is harder when fields are added/renamed. Projection logic is more complex.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Snapshot-style events (store full entity state in each event): Simpler event schema, easier projections. But wastes storage, obscures what actually changed, and makes audit diff queries harder."
      ]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Read model projections",
      "evolution_path": "New compliance requirements (e.g., 'show all applications touched by user X in date range') can be satisfied by adding a new projection that replays existing events. No write-side changes needed. This is event sourcing's superpower: events captured today answer questions not yet asked."
    },
    {
      "area": "Integration with downstream systems",
      "evolution_path": "The event stream can feed additional consumers: fraud detection, analytics, regulatory reporting systems. New subscribers are added without modifying the core loan origination logic."
    },
    {
      "area": "Audit query patterns",
      "evolution_path": "The Audit Projection can evolve independently. If regulators require new report formats, only the projection changes. The source events remain stable."
    },
    {
      "area": "Event store technology",
      "evolution_path": "Start with a relational event store table (PostgreSQL with append-only semantics). If scale demands it, migrate to a purpose-built event store (EventStoreDB, Axon) later. The abstraction boundary (EventStore interface) isolates this decision."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "Event schema",
      "reason": "Once events are persisted, their schema is immutable (you cannot change historical events). Event schema evolution must use careful strategies: upcasting (transforming old events to new schema on read), versioned event types (ApplicationSubmittedV2), or weak schema (storing events as JSON with tolerant readers). This is the hardest operational aspect of event sourcing and must be planned from day one."
    },
    {
      "area": "Aggregate boundaries",
      "reason": "The LoanApplication aggregate boundary determines the consistency and transactional scope. Changing it later (e.g., splitting into separate ApplicantProfile and LoanTerms aggregates) requires event migration, which is painful. Get the aggregate boundary right early."
    },
    {
      "area": "Event store immutability",
      "reason": "By design, events cannot be deleted or modified. This is a feature for compliance but a constraint for GDPR/data privacy (right to erasure). If PII is stored in events, a crypto-shredding strategy must be implemented from the start: encrypt PII fields with per-applicant keys, and 'delete' by destroying the key."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Event schema evolution complexity: As the loan application domain evolves, maintaining backward compatibility of events over years of historical data becomes a significant operational burden.",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Establish event versioning conventions from day one. Use upcasters to transform old events to current schema on read. Include a schema_version field in every event. Avoid breaking changes; prefer additive evolution (new fields with defaults, new event types)."
    },
    {
      "risk": "GDPR / Right to Erasure conflict: Immutable event store containing PII cannot satisfy deletion requests through simple row deletion.",
      "severity": "critical",
      "mitigation": "Implement crypto-shredding: encrypt PII fields in events using per-applicant encryption keys stored separately. To 'erase' an applicant, destroy their encryption key. This renders their PII in the event store irrecoverable while preserving event structure for audit. Design this into the event schema from the start — retrofitting is extremely difficult."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Team skill gap: Event sourcing + CQRS is a paradigm shift from CRUD. Incorrect implementation (e.g., treating events as database rows, mutable event semantics, missing idempotency) can create worse problems than the current system.",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Invest in team training before implementation. Start with a spike/proof-of-concept on a single workflow (e.g., status changes only). Consider hiring or consulting with someone experienced in event-sourced systems. Adopt a proven library/framework rather than building from scratch."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Performance degradation for long-lived aggregates: Loan applications that accumulate hundreds of events over months/years will have slow aggregate reconstruction times.",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Implement snapshotting from the start. Take a snapshot every N events (e.g., every 50). Aggregate reconstruction then loads the latest snapshot + subsequent events only."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Eventual consistency confusing the UI: After a loan officer updates an application, the read model may not reflect the change immediately, leading to confusion or duplicate submissions.",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "For this domain (low-volume, high-value transactions), consider synchronous projection updates within the command transaction. Loan applications are not high-throughput — the eventual consistency trade-off may not be worth the UX cost. Alternatively, use read-your-own-writes consistency: after a command succeeds, return the new version number and have the UI poll until the projection catches up."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Over-engineering: Event sourcing may be more complexity than needed if the real requirement is just an immutable audit log, not the full event sourcing paradigm.",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Honestly evaluate whether a simpler pattern (CDC + audit table, or bi-temporal modeling) satisfies the compliance requirements. Event sourcing is justified if: (a) point-in-time reconstruction is frequently needed, (b) the event stream has downstream consumers, (c) the domain has complex state machines. If the need is primarily 'keep a log of changes for regulators to review occasionally,' a simpler pattern may be more appropriate."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Implement event sourcing for the LoanApplication aggregate within the Loan Origination bounded context. Use PostgreSQL as the event store (append-only events table with optimistic concurrency via version column). Build CQRS read models for operational queries and a dedicated Audit Projection for compliance. Start with synchronous projection updates (in the same transaction) given the low throughput of loan applications, and move to async projections only if scale demands it. Implement crypto-shredding for PII from day one. Adopt a phased migration: (1) build the event-sourced system alongside the existing table, (2) dual-write during transition, (3) cut over reads, (4) decommission old table.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "src/loan/domain/events/ — Event type definitions (ApplicationCreated, StatusChanged, ApplicantInfoUpdated, etc.)",
      "src/loan/domain/LoanApplicationAggregate — Aggregate root with apply(event) methods for state reconstruction",
      "src/loan/infrastructure/PostgresEventStore — Append-only event persistence with optimistic concurrency",
      "src/loan/infrastructure/projections/LoanApplicationProjection — Operational read model",
      "src/loan/infrastructure/projections/AuditTrailProjection — Compliance-specific read model",
      "src/loan/application/commands/ — Command handlers (SubmitApplication, UpdateApplicantInfo, ChangeStatus)",
      "src/loan/application/queries/ — Query handlers against read models",
      "src/loan/infrastructure/crypto/PiiEncryptionService — Per-applicant encryption for crypto-shredding",
      "db/migrations/001_create_event_store.sql — events(aggregate_id, sequence_no, event_type, event_data JSONB, metadata JSONB, created_at), with unique constraint on (aggregate_id, sequence_no)",
      "db/migrations/002_create_snapshots.sql — snapshots(aggregate_id, version, state JSONB, created_at)",
      "db/migrations/003_create_audit_projection.sql — audit_trail(application_id, event_type, changed_fields JSONB, actor_id, timestamp, event_sequence)"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Each command handler: (1) load aggregate from event store, (2) call domain method which validates and returns new events, (3) append events to store with expected version, (4) update projections. Events are immutable value objects with metadata envelope. Aggregate has no setters — state changes only through event application. Read models are disposable and rebuildable.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "Do NOT store mutable state alongside events — the event stream is the single source of truth",
      "Do NOT use event sourcing for every bounded context — only where audit/history requirements justify the complexity",
      "Do NOT store PII in plain text in events — implement crypto-shredding from day one, not as a retrofit",
      "Do NOT skip the metadata envelope — every event must capture actor, timestamp, correlation ID",
      "Do NOT treat events as a log you append to and forget — events ARE the data model, they must be carefully designed",
      "Do NOT allow direct database access to bypass the command path — all mutations must go through the aggregate to enforce invariants",
      "Do NOT design events around your current UI forms — design events around domain state transitions"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 85,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "Event sourcing is a well-matched pattern for this use case — regulatory audit, immutable history, and point-in-time reconstruction are its core strengths",
      "CQRS is necessary companion to event sourcing for practical query support",
      "Crypto-shredding is the correct approach for GDPR compliance in an immutable event store",
      "PostgreSQL is a viable event store for this domain's throughput characteristics (loan applications are low-volume, high-value)"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Whether the team has sufficient experience to implement event sourcing correctly — this is the primary risk factor",
      "Whether the compliance requirements truly demand point-in-time reconstruction or merely a change log — if the latter, a simpler CDC + audit table pattern may be more appropriate and should be seriously considered",
      "Exact aggregate boundaries — need deeper domain knowledge about which fields change together and which invariants span multiple entities"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Loan application volume is low enough that PostgreSQL can serve as the event store (likely true — even large lenders process thousands, not millions, of applications per day)",
      "The compliance team needs programmatic point-in-time reconstruction, not just a human-readable change log",
      "The platform runs on infrastructure that supports PostgreSQL (or similar RDBMS)",
      "GDPR or similar data privacy regulations apply, necessitating crypto-shredding",
      "The team is willing to invest in learning event sourcing concepts and the associated operational overhead"
    ]
  }
}

